l Ordering -- tWe Were Here: Reclaiming African Canadian History Through Heritage Plaques -- tOn the Aggrecultural Poetics of Sonnet’s Shakespeare -- tMobilizing the Bard: Joseph Pierre’s Shakespeare’s Nigga (2013) -- tBuilding Black and Indigenous Alliances for HIV Prevention and Health Promotion -- tBlood is a Politic of Place-Making: Blackness, Queerness, and the Construction of the Donor -- tCreation is Legacy: Creativity and Futures -- tThe Story of Sister Vision: Black Women and Women of Colour Press -- tDub and the Right to Exist: An Interview with Lillian Allen -- tDub Pedagogies: An Interview with d’bi.young anitafrika -- tSpoken Word: A Signifying Gesture Toward Possibility -- twordsoundsystemsengineering: Meta-dub and Creation -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistoric freedom fighter and conductor of the Underground Railroad Harriet Tubman risked her life to ferry enslaved people from America to freedom in Canada. Her legacy instigates and orients this exploration of the history of Black lives and the future of collective struggle in Canada.Harriet’s Legacies recuperates the significance of Tubman’s time in Canada as more than just an interlude in her American narrative: it is a new point from which to think about Black diasporic mobilities, possibilities, and histories. Through essays and creative works this collection articulates new territory for Tubman in relation to the Black Atlantic archive, connecting her legacies of survival, freedom, and cultural expression within a transnational framework. Contributors take up the question of legacy in ways that remap discourses of genealogy and belonging, positioning Tubman as an important part of today’s freedom struggles. Integrating scholarship with creative and curatorial practices, the volume expands conversations about culture and expression in African Canadian life across art, literature, performance, politics, and public pedagogy.Considering questions of culture, community, and futures, Harriet’s Legacies explores what happened in the wake of Tubman’s legacy and situates Canada as a key part of that dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCanada. 0aBlack peoplezCanadaxHistory. 0aBlack peoplezCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aBlack peoplezCanada. 0aFugitive slaveszCanada. 0aUnderground RailroadzCanada. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aAfrican.  aAmerica.  aBlack.  aEssays.  aFreedom.  aGender.  aPedagogy.  aRace.  aRailroad.  aResistance.  aSlavery.  aTubman.  aUnderground.1 aAllen, Lillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroox, Klyde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroyld, dann j., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaple, Natalee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaple, Natalee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClarke, George Elliott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Afua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrooks, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuder-Domínguez, Pilar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDryden, OmiSoore H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlicker, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Karolyn Smardz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu